==German & Yiddish==
===Etymology===
From [[Low German]] and [[Yiddish]] [[שמאָק]] ''shmok'', literally ''[[penis]]'' (''vulgar''), from Old Polish [[smok]] (modern Polish: [[smok]], ''dragon)''.

==German==
===Noun===
'''Schmuck''' ''m''
#''[[jewelry]]''
#''[[ornament]]'', ''[[decoration]]''
# something that is considered overly [[sentimental]]
# ([[pejorative]]) an item or person that is considered [[useless]]

==Yiddish==
===Noun===
'''shmuck''' or '''schmuck'''
# ([[vulgar]]) the ''[[penis]]''
# ([[vulgar]]) the ''[[foreskin]]''
# a piece of [[decoration]] or [[ornament]]
# ([[pejorative]]) an item or person that is considered [[useless]]
# a [[derogatory]] description of an individual (usually a man)

===Adjective===
'''schmucklich''' or '''shmucklich'''
# old-fashioned for ''[[pretty]]'', ''[[spruce]]d up'', ''[[decorated]]''

